1
00:00:14,055 --> 00:00:19,894
NO VISITORS ALLOWED

2
00:00:32,657 --> 00:00:36,369
CLUB WITHDRAWAL FORM

3
00:00:36,453 --> 00:00:38,747
When we lost our first match at nationals…

4
00:00:40,999 --> 00:00:43,001
one of the guys cried in the locker room

5
00:00:43,585 --> 00:00:46,212
and said,
"If only Ryu and Arata were here."

6
00:00:47,630 --> 00:00:51,634
That was when Seiichi blew up,
which almost never happens.

7
00:00:53,428 --> 00:00:56,473
He said, "We're the ones
that cornered them."

8
00:01:05,273 --> 00:01:07,067
Seiichi is right.

9
00:01:09,069 --> 00:01:10,070
I'm sorry.

10
00:01:12,447 --> 00:01:13,448
It's fine.

11
00:01:15,408 --> 00:01:16,868
What will you do after you quit?

12
00:01:20,663 --> 00:01:21,998
I don't know.

13
00:01:23,792 --> 00:01:28,797
But I do know something has to change.

14
00:01:39,557 --> 00:01:40,642
Ryu.

15
00:01:48,441 --> 00:01:50,026
Don't quit school.

16
00:01:51,861 --> 00:01:54,489
What's the point in staying
if I'm not playing ice hockey?

17
00:01:54,572 --> 00:01:55,740
Listen.

18
00:02:03,289 --> 00:02:05,041
College is where you learn.

19
00:02:06,918 --> 00:02:08,837
It's where you meet people.

20
00:02:10,630 --> 00:02:15,135
Ice hockey is only a fraction
of your time here.

21
00:02:17,470 --> 00:02:18,596
Yeah, but…

22
00:02:18,680 --> 00:02:20,723
I'll speak to Student Affairs

23
00:02:21,432 --> 00:02:26,271
so that you won't lose the tuition waiver
from your athletic scholarship.

24
00:02:34,028 --> 00:02:34,904
Please.

25
00:02:36,072 --> 00:02:40,910
I don't want to crush the team's future.

26
00:02:54,340 --> 00:02:55,717
Seiichi.

27
00:02:59,888 --> 00:03:01,097
Ryu!

28
00:03:02,098 --> 00:03:04,851
Ryu!

29
00:03:04,934 --> 00:03:06,060
What the hell?

30
00:03:06,895 --> 00:03:08,396
-Ryu!
-Hey.

31
00:03:09,772 --> 00:03:12,233
Well, come on.

32
00:03:17,614 --> 00:03:19,574
You're seriously quitting?

33
00:03:21,034 --> 00:03:22,035
Yeah.

34
00:03:25,330 --> 00:03:27,957
Do you remember
the first time we met in college?

35
00:03:28,958 --> 00:03:29,959
Yeah.

36
00:03:30,877 --> 00:03:34,005
"I'm Super Scrappy Seiichi," right?

37
00:03:34,672 --> 00:03:35,882
No.

38
00:03:36,758 --> 00:03:39,135
It's, "I'm Super Scrappy Seiichi!"

39
00:03:39,802 --> 00:03:41,512
There it is. The original version.

40
00:03:42,764 --> 00:03:46,684
We actually met when we faced off
at the high school nationals.

41
00:03:46,768 --> 00:03:49,479
But you didn't remember me at all.

42
00:03:50,438 --> 00:03:52,315
I said I was sorry.

43
00:03:52,815 --> 00:03:54,359
You should be.

44
00:03:55,026 --> 00:03:59,572
Well, you and Arata were
a cut above the rest in high school.

45
00:04:00,073 --> 00:04:04,494
I was thrilled when I found out
we were going to the same college.

46
00:04:04,577 --> 00:04:07,455
I was determined to become a starter
and play with you.

47
00:04:09,749 --> 00:04:12,460
Life sure is strange, huh?

48
00:04:13,711 --> 00:04:16,214
You guys have crazy talent,
yet you're quitting,

49
00:04:17,465 --> 00:04:20,635
while someone like me is still playing.

50
00:04:21,970 --> 00:04:24,973
What do you mean, "someone like me"?

51
00:04:27,558 --> 00:04:31,312
What will you do after leaving the dorm?
Where will you live?

52
00:04:31,813 --> 00:04:32,939
About that,

53
00:04:33,439 --> 00:04:37,026
I thought about dropping out
and going back to my hometown.

54
00:04:37,110 --> 00:04:38,027
Yeah?

55
00:04:38,111 --> 00:04:40,530
But I'll look for a place tomorrow.

56
00:04:40,613 --> 00:04:42,490
I haven't told my parents yet though.

57
00:04:42,573 --> 00:04:43,574
Wait.

58
00:04:44,325 --> 00:04:45,868
-Hey.
-What?

59
00:04:45,952 --> 00:04:47,537
Can I come over sometime?

60
00:04:47,620 --> 00:04:48,621
What?

61
00:04:49,956 --> 00:04:52,208
Well, sure.

62
00:04:52,709 --> 00:04:54,877
All right!

63
00:04:55,670 --> 00:04:59,299
Man, having your own place is the best.

64
00:04:59,382 --> 00:05:01,592
You can do whatever you want.

65
00:05:02,385 --> 00:05:07,265
I wanna break out of this dorm
and get a girlfriend.

66
00:05:07,348 --> 00:05:09,100
The dorm's not the problem.

67
00:05:09,183 --> 00:05:10,518
It is too!

68
00:05:11,394 --> 00:05:13,813
I couldn't properly join
the parade last year.

69
00:05:13,896 --> 00:05:15,732
Join us. You're coming, aren't you?

70
00:05:15,815 --> 00:05:16,941
Of course.

71
00:05:17,442 --> 00:05:19,360
See you then. Enjoy your meal.

72
00:05:24,407 --> 00:05:27,952
I can't believe you're reading manga
while drinking.

73
00:05:29,454 --> 00:05:30,913
It's my choice.

74
00:05:30,997 --> 00:05:33,458
Man, you're so not cute.

75
00:05:33,541 --> 00:05:34,876
Another.

76
00:05:35,460 --> 00:05:38,671
Instead of drinking here all the time,
go make some friends.

77
00:05:47,096 --> 00:05:48,306
Huh? What is it?

78
00:05:48,890 --> 00:05:49,724
Huh?

79
00:05:50,641 --> 00:05:51,559
You made a friend?

80
00:05:51,642 --> 00:05:52,727
What?

81
00:05:53,227 --> 00:05:55,063
-Who is it?
-You're so nosy.

82
00:05:55,897 --> 00:05:57,732
Come on, tell me!

83
00:05:57,815 --> 00:06:01,277
Ugh, give me a break.
I'm trying to focus on my manga.

84
00:06:01,778 --> 00:06:04,781
Don't be like that.
Bring your new friend over next time.

85
00:06:29,347 --> 00:06:31,974
RYU: I QUIT ICE HOCKEY.
I WON'T DROP OUT OF COLLEGE.

86
00:06:32,058 --> 00:06:33,643
NOT SURE WHAT TO DO THOUGH.

87
00:06:37,855 --> 00:06:41,859
JUST BE GLAD YOU GET TO GO TO COLLEGE.

88
00:06:41,943 --> 00:06:45,655
I'M RETIRING TOMORROW.

89
00:07:08,219 --> 00:07:10,805
RYU: GOOD LUCK.

90
00:07:10,888 --> 00:07:12,807
"Good luck"? Is he for real?

91
00:07:49,051 --> 00:07:51,637
Last one! Push harder!

92
00:08:01,606 --> 00:08:02,607
Last one!

93
00:08:17,663 --> 00:08:18,873
It's over.

94
00:08:27,256 --> 00:08:28,341
That Shim Gicheol…

95
00:08:30,134 --> 00:08:32,470
He went around tempting other boxers too.

96
00:08:36,098 --> 00:08:38,434
Someone leaked it.

97
00:08:39,310 --> 00:08:41,437
The association will be kicking him out.

98
00:08:45,775 --> 00:08:47,026
I'm sorry.

99
00:08:51,572 --> 00:08:53,741
What are you sorry for?

100
00:08:54,659 --> 00:08:55,952
Forget it.

101
00:09:02,291 --> 00:09:06,837
None of the boxers in Korea
have any money.

102
00:09:10,174 --> 00:09:12,134
But they still continue to box.

103
00:09:13,427 --> 00:09:16,097
Who would willingly do
something like that…

104
00:09:18,266 --> 00:09:20,476
after enduring
this hellish training every day?

105
00:09:37,326 --> 00:09:38,411
Johan.

106
00:09:40,246 --> 00:09:46,043
You were a troublemaker
from the moment you got here.

107
00:09:47,753 --> 00:09:52,466
But that troublemaker's eyes
were brighter…

108
00:09:54,927 --> 00:09:56,387
than anyone else's.

109
00:09:59,056 --> 00:10:00,433
Back then…

110
00:10:04,562 --> 00:10:05,730
and even now.

111
00:10:18,951 --> 00:10:20,161
Thank you so much…

112
00:10:23,623 --> 00:10:25,082
for everything.

113
00:10:34,133 --> 00:10:35,176
All right.

114
00:10:40,222 --> 00:10:41,140
Last one.

115
00:10:42,850 --> 00:10:43,684
One more time.

116
00:10:53,569 --> 00:10:57,406
You will be doing on-site training
at a nursing home,

117
00:10:57,490 --> 00:11:00,785
which is required
to earn credits for this course.

118
00:11:00,868 --> 00:11:01,869
Ow!

119
00:11:02,953 --> 00:11:04,038
As written in the syllabus…

120
00:11:04,121 --> 00:11:05,122
Hey.

121
00:11:06,582 --> 00:11:07,667
Is it over?

122
00:11:07,750 --> 00:11:08,584
Not yet.

123
00:11:09,710 --> 00:11:10,711
Gross.

124
00:11:10,795 --> 00:11:12,755
I slept so well.

125
00:11:15,800 --> 00:11:19,053
Two, two, three. Three, two, three.

126
00:12:19,280 --> 00:12:21,532
<i>Annyeonghaseyo</i>.

127
00:12:22,324 --> 00:12:24,827
<i>Huh? Are you drunk?</i>

128
00:12:26,454 --> 00:12:28,998
I sure am. Got a problem with that?

129
00:12:30,416 --> 00:12:32,626
You're not good with alcohol.

130
00:12:33,210 --> 00:12:34,503
<i>Oh, come on.</i>

131
00:12:38,007 --> 00:12:41,886
So, how was your retirement?
Did you have a ceremony?

132
00:12:41,969 --> 00:12:43,637
A ceremony?

133
00:12:44,972 --> 00:12:48,184
Why would I have one?
I wasn't even a champion.

134
00:12:49,185 --> 00:12:52,646
Just like always, I jogged,

135
00:12:52,730 --> 00:12:54,690
<i>sparred, and that was it.</i>

136
00:12:55,191 --> 00:12:56,192
I see.

137
00:12:58,861 --> 00:13:04,366
<i>I also stayed for drinks with the coach.</i>

138
00:13:05,242 --> 00:13:06,786
-You did?
-<i>Yeah.</i>

139
00:13:07,286 --> 00:13:08,829
Good job.

140
00:13:11,081 --> 00:13:12,958
<i>Show more respect.</i>

141
00:13:14,210 --> 00:13:16,253
I'm surprised you know
such a difficult word.

142
00:13:16,337 --> 00:13:18,756
Of course I do.

143
00:13:19,256 --> 00:13:22,343
"Respect" is fundamental for Koreans.

144
00:13:24,637 --> 00:13:25,930
Is that so?

145
00:13:26,806 --> 00:13:28,098
<i>It is.</i>

146
00:13:31,018 --> 00:13:32,394
It's over.

147
00:13:34,230 --> 00:13:39,401
Now I can eat as much as I want.
<i>Jjajangmyeon</i>, <i>jjamppong</i>, chicken, pizza.

148
00:13:41,612 --> 00:13:43,572
<i>Are you happy you quit boxing?</i>

149
00:13:43,656 --> 00:13:45,699
Yeah, I am.

150
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:48,953
Aren't you happy?

151
00:13:49,453 --> 00:13:53,290
You can do whatever you want
from here on out.

152
00:13:56,252 --> 00:14:00,256
Don't you ever feel lost?

153
00:14:00,840 --> 00:14:02,007
<i>Well…</i>

154
00:14:06,929 --> 00:14:09,974
<i>Getting lost is a good thing.</i>

155
00:14:14,728 --> 00:14:17,731
I'm starting my military service.

156
00:14:20,568 --> 00:14:22,236
Huh? For how long?

157
00:14:23,737 --> 00:14:24,989
<i>About two years.</i>

158
00:14:26,699 --> 00:14:28,576
Two years?

159
00:14:31,078 --> 00:14:33,747
Is that short? Or long?

160
00:14:34,874 --> 00:14:37,501
<i>Jeez, that's long.</i>

161
00:14:40,254 --> 00:14:43,549
Koreans are obligated to serve.
I have no choice.

162
00:14:44,425 --> 00:14:48,721
But you Japanese people can use that time

163
00:14:49,221 --> 00:14:51,223
to wander.

164
00:14:52,433 --> 00:14:55,728
You can take your time
figuring out what you want to do.

165
00:14:58,230 --> 00:14:59,648
Isn't that a good thing?

166
00:15:09,575 --> 00:15:10,826
You think there'll be any?

167
00:15:10,910 --> 00:15:11,911
Huh?

168
00:15:14,788 --> 00:15:16,749
You think there'll be any young girls?

169
00:15:21,587 --> 00:15:23,505
We're almost there. You can do it.

170
00:15:23,589 --> 00:15:25,382
Come on.

171
00:15:27,676 --> 00:15:29,929
-I don't wanna anymore.
-What?

172
00:15:32,097 --> 00:15:33,390
You wanna head back?

173
00:15:37,269 --> 00:15:39,688
A bit further. That was close!

174
00:15:39,772 --> 00:15:41,523
-Yes!
-So close.

175
00:15:42,358 --> 00:15:44,151
-All right. Here!
-Go!

176
00:15:44,652 --> 00:15:46,820
You got it. Nice!

177
00:15:49,114 --> 00:15:53,535
Take the top sheet
and align it with the bottom.

178
00:15:54,495 --> 00:15:55,704
Like this.

179
00:15:55,788 --> 00:15:57,289
-That's right.
-I'm good.

180
00:15:57,373 --> 00:15:59,041
-So fast.
-Right?

181
00:15:59,124 --> 00:16:01,001
-How was that?
-Not bad for your first time.

182
00:16:01,085 --> 00:16:02,795
-Oh, thank you.
-Thank you.

183
00:16:02,878 --> 00:16:05,255
Should we do that one next?

184
00:16:05,339 --> 00:16:06,590
-This one too?
-Yes.

185
00:16:06,674 --> 00:16:10,302
-Okay.
-I'll go over to the head side.

186
00:16:12,554 --> 00:16:14,390
Take the top…

187
00:16:17,643 --> 00:16:18,811
Dammit.

188
00:16:18,894 --> 00:16:21,605
Man, this is so tough.

189
00:16:22,147 --> 00:16:23,649
What are we doing here?

190
00:16:23,732 --> 00:16:25,275
This is exhausting.

191
00:16:26,276 --> 00:16:27,903
Practice isn't as tiring as this.

192
00:16:28,821 --> 00:16:32,491
How is pulling weeds
part of our training, anyway?

193
00:16:32,574 --> 00:16:34,159
What's this gotta do with caregiving?

194
00:16:34,243 --> 00:16:35,244
Hey.

195
00:16:36,078 --> 00:16:37,663
Will you focus on your work?

196
00:16:38,414 --> 00:16:39,790
-Yes, ma'am.
-Yes, ma'am.

197
00:16:40,290 --> 00:16:42,376
When you're done, carry that over.

198
00:16:42,459 --> 00:16:43,669
Then, it's bathing time.

199
00:16:50,175 --> 00:16:51,343
She's a young girl.

200
00:16:53,846 --> 00:16:55,472
Nah.

201
00:16:56,098 --> 00:17:00,227
I prefer someone nicer and more ladylike.

202
00:17:01,395 --> 00:17:03,147
Will you answer me?

203
00:17:03,814 --> 00:17:05,274
-Yes, ma'am!
-Yes, ma'am!

204
00:17:09,069 --> 00:17:10,988
This is so much.

205
00:17:11,071 --> 00:17:12,114
Huh?

206
00:17:12,197 --> 00:17:16,952
I mean, this isn't what I imagined.

207
00:17:17,703 --> 00:17:19,955
The job is physically demanding.

208
00:17:21,248 --> 00:17:22,708
Are you being sarcastic?

209
00:17:23,709 --> 00:17:25,711
No, that wasn't my intention.

210
00:17:26,462 --> 00:17:29,131
I can't stand people like you guys.

211
00:17:29,757 --> 00:17:32,342
-We don't like you either.
-What?

212
00:17:33,510 --> 00:17:34,678
Oh, sorry.

213
00:17:34,762 --> 00:17:37,556
This might be
part of your course or whatever,

214
00:17:37,639 --> 00:17:42,102
but I don't get paid a cent
for babysitting you two.

215
00:17:42,186 --> 00:17:44,313
Ugh, hey. Not that way.

216
00:17:44,396 --> 00:17:46,565
It's this way. To the right.

217
00:17:49,735 --> 00:17:50,819
Are you okay?

218
00:17:51,320 --> 00:17:52,362
Yeah.

219
00:17:52,946 --> 00:17:55,783
How is this? Am I scrubbing too hard?

220
00:17:55,866 --> 00:18:00,245
No. It feels nice.

221
00:18:00,746 --> 00:18:02,247
Good.

222
00:18:03,040 --> 00:18:04,750
Do you feel itchy anywhere?

223
00:18:04,833 --> 00:18:07,169
Oh, that's nice.

224
00:18:11,340 --> 00:18:13,008
Can you turn the water off?

225
00:18:13,092 --> 00:18:14,093
Sure.

226
00:18:14,760 --> 00:18:17,137
All right, let's rinse you off.

227
00:18:17,221 --> 00:18:19,306
Thank you.

228
00:18:19,389 --> 00:18:20,474
Here we go.

229
00:18:22,768 --> 00:18:24,603
Yeah, I'm heading back tomorrow.

230
00:18:25,896 --> 00:18:28,482
Yeah, I got a ticket from the Busta.

231
00:18:29,817 --> 00:18:32,444
Huh? No, from the Busta.

232
00:18:33,862 --> 00:18:36,907
Not pasta. Busta.

233
00:18:38,242 --> 00:18:41,286
Yeah.

234
00:18:42,955 --> 00:18:44,540
Sorry, I have to hang up now.

235
00:18:44,623 --> 00:18:46,708
Yeah. Okay, bye.

236
00:18:50,462 --> 00:18:51,964
<i>Surprise.</i>

237
00:18:52,923 --> 00:18:53,924
What?

238
00:18:56,301 --> 00:18:59,263
<i>Guess where I am right now.</i>

239
00:19:01,014 --> 00:19:02,266
Where?

240
00:19:03,016 --> 00:19:05,144
I don't even know where you live in Korea.

241
00:19:07,312 --> 00:19:09,189
<i>I'm at Narita Airport.</i>

242
00:19:09,273 --> 00:19:10,274
What?

243
00:19:10,774 --> 00:19:13,068
<i>Where do you live?</i>

244
00:19:14,820 --> 00:19:15,946
<i>Seriously?</i>

245
00:19:43,807 --> 00:19:44,975
<i>Annyeong</i>.

246
00:19:45,601 --> 00:19:47,352
"<i>Annyeong</i>"?

247
00:19:47,436 --> 00:19:50,522
This really is a surprise.
You should've told me you were coming.

248
00:19:50,606 --> 00:19:52,858
Then it wouldn’t have been a surprise.

249
00:19:52,941 --> 00:19:54,735
Well, that's true, but…

250
00:19:55,235 --> 00:19:57,362
What? Aren't you happy to see me?

251
00:19:58,447 --> 00:19:59,948
I guess I am.

252
00:20:00,032 --> 00:20:01,116
Then it's fine.

253
00:20:01,742 --> 00:20:04,912
What were you gonna do
if I already had plans?

254
00:20:11,126 --> 00:20:12,294
Wait, I do.

255
00:20:13,045 --> 00:20:14,171
What?

256
00:20:14,254 --> 00:20:15,088
I have plans.

257
00:20:15,172 --> 00:20:18,300
Well, a friend suddenly came over.

258
00:20:19,760 --> 00:20:22,888
Uh, it's a guy I met a while back.

259
00:20:24,598 --> 00:20:27,601
No, he's not from college.

260
00:20:28,101 --> 00:20:29,228
Yeah.

261
00:20:29,311 --> 00:20:30,812
He's not Japanese.

262
00:20:40,781 --> 00:20:41,782
Wow.

263
00:20:42,824 --> 00:20:44,076
They said it's fine.

264
00:20:45,535 --> 00:20:47,329
-They did?
-Yeah.

265
00:20:47,412 --> 00:20:48,413
By the way,

266
00:20:49,248 --> 00:20:50,874
why are you going home?

267
00:20:53,252 --> 00:20:54,461
Wait one second.

268
00:20:56,797 --> 00:20:58,966
Let's see.

269
00:20:59,049 --> 00:21:00,842
In Korean, it's…

270
00:21:00,926 --> 00:21:01,927
Yeah?

271
00:21:02,886 --> 00:21:04,846
-Whoa!
-Huh?

272
00:21:04,930 --> 00:21:05,889
Sorry, I missed it.

273
00:21:05,973 --> 00:21:07,140
Dammit.

274
00:21:07,224 --> 00:21:08,350
<i>Chesa</i>?

275
00:21:09,017 --> 00:21:10,394
<i>J-Jesa</i>?

276
00:21:11,812 --> 00:21:12,688
<i>Jesa</i>?

277
00:21:12,771 --> 00:21:13,855
Yeah.

278
00:21:16,858 --> 00:21:18,819
Are you sure it's okay?

279
00:21:19,319 --> 00:21:21,613
Don't start worrying now.

280
00:21:22,281 --> 00:21:23,282
Um…

281
00:21:24,449 --> 00:21:30,080
But <i>jesa </i>is an important day for families.

282
00:21:31,081 --> 00:21:33,834
My parents were actually
kind of happy about this.

283
00:21:34,459 --> 00:21:35,544
Okay.

284
00:21:36,044 --> 00:21:37,212
Thanks.

285
00:21:37,296 --> 00:21:39,548
By the way,
how long are you staying in Japan?

286
00:21:40,257 --> 00:21:41,425
Two nights.

287
00:21:42,926 --> 00:21:43,927
I see.

288
00:21:46,805 --> 00:21:48,056
Are you feeling sad?

289
00:21:49,891 --> 00:21:52,227
It's just shorter than I thought.

290
00:21:53,270 --> 00:21:55,022
I need to prepare for the military.

291
00:21:55,105 --> 00:21:56,231
Yeah.

292
00:22:01,111 --> 00:22:04,031
Since you're in Tokyo,
is there anywhere you want to go?

293
00:22:08,076 --> 00:22:08,910
There is.

294
00:22:16,835 --> 00:22:17,836
Oh!

295
00:22:17,919 --> 00:22:19,546
<i>Blade of the Immortal.</i>

296
00:22:21,715 --> 00:22:23,008
So old-school.

297
00:22:23,091 --> 00:22:24,092
Huh?

298
00:22:24,634 --> 00:22:25,802
Samurai.

299
00:22:25,886 --> 00:22:27,304
Samu…

300
00:22:27,387 --> 00:22:29,222
That's more like a ninja.

301
00:22:31,266 --> 00:22:33,727
No! It's that one.

302
00:22:34,728 --> 00:22:35,937
Sorry.

303
00:22:38,690 --> 00:22:41,109
Don't you have manga cafés in Korea?

304
00:22:42,861 --> 00:22:44,905
-We do.
-You do?

305
00:22:45,614 --> 00:22:47,908
-We do.
-Oh, you do have them.

306
00:22:47,991 --> 00:22:48,825
Yeah.

307
00:22:49,326 --> 00:22:50,327
Okay.

308
00:22:51,203 --> 00:22:52,371
Nothing.

309
00:22:52,454 --> 00:22:53,455
Shh.

310
00:22:58,585 --> 00:23:00,170
-Is this mackerel?
-Yeah.

311
00:23:01,129 --> 00:23:02,464
Okay, the mackerel.

312
00:23:05,425 --> 00:23:06,760
Mm, <i>masitda</i>!

313
00:23:06,843 --> 00:23:09,388
-Oh, I'm glad.
-Yeah.

314
00:23:16,269 --> 00:23:17,938
-Yeah, <i>masitda</i>.
-<i>Masitda.</i>

315
00:23:18,021 --> 00:23:18,855
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

316
00:23:18,939 --> 00:23:22,401
By the way, how old are you?

317
00:23:22,484 --> 00:23:24,111
I'm 21.

318
00:23:24,611 --> 00:23:27,239
I see. Hmm?

319
00:23:27,322 --> 00:23:28,407
-Then…
-Yeah?

320
00:23:31,326 --> 00:23:32,536
You…

321
00:23:34,871 --> 00:23:38,041
will drink like this from now on.

322
00:23:42,587 --> 00:23:44,798
-I've seen that in Korean dramas.
-Yeah.

323
00:23:45,590 --> 00:23:46,967
In Korea,

324
00:23:47,676 --> 00:23:52,514
seniors and juniors drink differently.

325
00:23:53,265 --> 00:23:55,183
Which way of drinking was that?

326
00:23:55,267 --> 00:23:56,601
The junior way.

327
00:23:58,812 --> 00:24:00,230
What year were you born?

328
00:24:00,313 --> 00:24:01,648
-Huh? Me?
-Yeah.

329
00:24:02,149 --> 00:24:03,400
I was born in

330
00:24:04,526 --> 00:24:10,991
19… 95.

331
00:24:11,074 --> 00:24:13,660
-What? Then we're the same age.
-No.

332
00:24:13,743 --> 00:24:15,245
-You're 21.
-No.

333
00:24:16,037 --> 00:24:19,040
I'm considered 22 years old in Korea.

334
00:24:19,124 --> 00:24:20,667
-What?
-Yes.

335
00:24:20,750 --> 00:24:24,629
I'm Korean. You're Japanese.

336
00:24:26,381 --> 00:24:30,594
We count ages differently
depending on what country we're from.

337
00:24:30,677 --> 00:24:32,137
That's my rule.

338
00:24:32,762 --> 00:24:35,307
What's with that weird rule?

339
00:24:35,390 --> 00:24:39,060
That's why I'm gonna drink like this.

340
00:24:45,442 --> 00:24:47,110
Are Korean apartments like this too?

341
00:24:47,194 --> 00:24:48,862
-No.
-They're not?

342
00:24:48,945 --> 00:24:50,947
-They're tall.
-I see.

343
00:24:53,992 --> 00:24:56,036
-My room's upstairs. Second floor.
-Okay.

344
00:24:58,455 --> 00:24:59,581
It's nice.

345
00:25:00,081 --> 00:25:01,708
-Is it?
-Yeah.

346
00:25:04,794 --> 00:25:06,254
Wow.

347
00:25:06,963 --> 00:25:09,424
Thanks for having me.

348
00:25:09,508 --> 00:25:10,550
Come in.

349
00:25:11,593 --> 00:25:13,094
There we go.

350
00:25:21,520 --> 00:25:22,521
Whoa.

351
00:25:27,442 --> 00:25:30,779
KOREAN FOR BEGINNERS

352
00:25:40,914 --> 00:25:43,250
You can dump your stuff over there.

353
00:25:43,959 --> 00:25:45,293
Okay.

354
00:25:46,545 --> 00:25:47,921
Man! What the hell?!

355
00:26:04,354 --> 00:26:05,855
It doesn't work.

356
00:26:05,939 --> 00:26:06,940
Yeah.

357
00:26:08,149 --> 00:26:09,734
The light's dead.

358
00:26:55,780 --> 00:26:57,365
NISHINASUNO SHIOBARA

359
00:27:05,999 --> 00:27:07,751
Nasu.

360
00:27:07,834 --> 00:27:09,169
-Huh?
-We're here.

361
00:27:09,252 --> 00:27:10,879
-Nasu?
-Yeah.

362
00:27:25,810 --> 00:27:27,896
-Welcome home.
-I'm back.

363
00:27:31,149 --> 00:27:32,984
-Here.
-Oh.

364
00:27:33,068 --> 00:27:34,986
My mom and dad.

365
00:27:35,820 --> 00:27:37,906
Nice to meet you. I'm Hwang Johan.

366
00:27:39,240 --> 00:27:41,201
You're so handsome!

367
00:27:41,284 --> 00:27:43,578
Welcome!

368
00:27:51,461 --> 00:27:57,258
Today is the 13th anniversary
of my little brother's death.

369
00:27:59,469 --> 00:28:03,932
My brother was a painter.
He was always painting.

370
00:28:06,142 --> 00:28:10,814
When Ryu was seven, he suddenly said,
"I want to paint the ocean,"

371
00:28:12,190 --> 00:28:14,567
and moved to Kyushu.

372
00:28:16,319 --> 00:28:17,153
You see,

373
00:28:18,071 --> 00:28:19,906
we don't have an ocean around here.

374
00:28:23,118 --> 00:28:26,204
I know I shouldn't say this
as his older brother,

375
00:28:27,664 --> 00:28:29,708
<i>but he was an eccentric guy.</i>

376
00:28:30,625 --> 00:28:31,876
I guess

377
00:28:32,877 --> 00:28:35,505
when he was focused on something,

378
00:28:35,588 --> 00:28:40,677
he would get lost in that world
for a long time.

379
00:28:41,845 --> 00:28:42,929
And…

380
00:28:45,348 --> 00:28:47,684
he died because of the ocean.

381
00:29:02,949 --> 00:29:04,325
There we go.

382
00:29:18,298 --> 00:29:20,467
Oh, right.

383
00:29:20,550 --> 00:29:27,557
There's a house nearby
that my brother used as an art studio.

384
00:29:30,393 --> 00:29:33,521
Maybe you could show it to Johan
if he'd like that.

385
00:29:34,147 --> 00:29:35,565
-Right?
-Yeah.

386
00:29:35,648 --> 00:29:38,818
Your uncle would be thrilled. Right?

387
00:29:38,902 --> 00:29:39,903
How about it?

388
00:29:41,946 --> 00:29:42,989
I'd love to.

389
00:29:45,116 --> 00:29:47,410
-I'll drive them there.
-Okay.

390
00:29:48,244 --> 00:29:49,454
Right. Let's clean up.

391
00:29:55,293 --> 00:29:56,753
Have a safe drive back.

392
00:30:04,886 --> 00:30:07,347
-All right. Wanna go in?
-Okay.

393
00:30:14,896 --> 00:30:17,273
You keep the key in a place like that?

394
00:30:18,149 --> 00:30:20,276
That's how it is
in the countryside in Japan.

395
00:30:22,237 --> 00:30:23,446
How peaceful.

396
00:30:24,864 --> 00:30:26,533
-Come in.
-Okay.

397
00:30:37,210 --> 00:30:39,087
This is the art studio.

398
00:30:39,170 --> 00:30:40,171
I see.

399
00:31:27,260 --> 00:31:31,514
My uncle was working on this painting
until the very end.

400
00:31:41,441 --> 00:31:42,734
This painting…

401
00:31:46,487 --> 00:31:47,739
feels sad.

402
00:31:54,537 --> 00:31:55,788
Where is this?

403
00:32:00,460 --> 00:32:01,753
I wonder.

404
00:32:04,547 --> 00:32:06,174
But I think…

405
00:32:08,551 --> 00:32:11,804
he painted it while thinking
of someone special to him.

406
00:32:19,395 --> 00:32:20,480
I see.

407
00:32:27,195 --> 00:32:28,321
<i>Hey, Ryu.</i>

408
00:32:29,322 --> 00:32:31,157
What do you think loneliness is?

409
00:32:34,619 --> 00:32:37,413
Always being by yourself

410
00:32:37,914 --> 00:32:40,750
without any friends.

411
00:32:41,584 --> 00:32:42,502
Being alone!

412
00:32:46,381 --> 00:32:48,675
Is that how you see me?

413
00:32:49,175 --> 00:32:52,929
Well, if you move far away,
we can't see each other, right?

414
00:32:58,559 --> 00:33:00,603
Well, then. Okay.

415
00:33:01,396 --> 00:33:03,648
Ryu, come over here.

416
00:33:03,731 --> 00:33:06,693
Yeah. Now, up you go.

417
00:33:06,776 --> 00:33:09,362
I've got paint all over my hands.

418
00:33:10,530 --> 00:33:12,281
I'm a zombie!

419
00:33:16,494 --> 00:33:17,870
-It's a lot, isn't it?
-Yeah.

420
00:33:17,954 --> 00:33:18,955
Right?

421
00:33:25,294 --> 00:33:26,921
You know, loneliness is…

422
00:33:30,466 --> 00:33:32,093
Loneliness is

423
00:33:33,594 --> 00:33:38,891
probably the feeling of not having
anyone you truly care about.

424
00:33:39,392 --> 00:33:41,102
-Hmm?
-Well…

425
00:33:41,853 --> 00:33:45,690
I've got a lot of people
that I care about.

426
00:33:46,899 --> 00:33:51,988
When you feel lonely,
try looking at the scenery somewhere.

427
00:33:52,071 --> 00:33:54,115
It doesn't matter where.

428
00:33:55,199 --> 00:33:57,076
The scenery?

429
00:33:57,160 --> 00:33:58,536
Yes, that's right.

430
00:34:00,955 --> 00:34:02,123
The scenery…

431
00:34:04,250 --> 00:34:05,668
mirrors your heart.

432
00:34:06,711 --> 00:34:10,673
If you look at it for a while
and think, "It's pretty,"

433
00:34:10,757 --> 00:34:13,009
or "It brings back memories,"

434
00:34:13,092 --> 00:34:18,264
that's because you once saw that scenery
with someone you treasured.

435
00:34:18,765 --> 00:34:24,103
And you can find
that treasured person in any scenery.

436
00:34:24,729 --> 00:34:25,938
Do you get why?

437
00:34:27,065 --> 00:34:29,650
Because the scenery mirrors your heart.

438
00:34:31,152 --> 00:34:32,528
Do you really get it?

439
00:34:32,612 --> 00:34:34,614
-I get it.
-Do you?

440
00:34:34,697 --> 00:34:38,451
-Then do you see anyone in this scenery?
-No.

441
00:34:38,534 --> 00:34:39,869
What about that one?

442
00:34:40,369 --> 00:34:41,370
No.

443
00:34:42,997 --> 00:34:45,374
<i>But one day, you might find someone there.</i>

444
00:34:45,875 --> 00:34:46,876
<i>Okay?</i>

445
00:37:36,545 --> 00:37:39,465
Subtitle translation by: Remi Miura
